## Reusable knowledge

- The technically plausible clone surface is the runtime/app-server layer: official Codex docs describe an app-server using JSON-RPC plus project-scoped threads, worktrees, Git tools, and Local/Worktree/Cloud modes, while the full desktop UI is not open source [Task 1]
- Official Claude Code surfaces expose runtime status fields including `context_window`, `rate_limits`, `effort.level`, and `thinking.enabled`, so a Codex-like app can surface those fields when available instead of inventing parallel state [Task 1]
- `claude -p` with `--output-format stream-json` is the stable integration path; prefer that over terminal scraping, and pair it with `--resume`, `--allowedTools`, and `--permission-mode` as the app matures [Task 2]
- `claude auth status` is the clean auth verification path; the validated local state here was `loggedIn: true`, `authMethod: "claude.ai"`, `apiProvider: "firstParty"`, `subscriptionType: "max"` [Task 2]
- `--bare` is the wrong mode when the goal is subscription auth because it skips OAuth/keychain reads, and a present `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` can switch billing away from the subscription path [Task 2]
- The validated implementation shape was Electron/React UI plus typed IPC, a long-lived agent-host/runtime process, SQLite project/thread indexing, Git/worktree services, and feature-detected usage/mode surfaces rather than renderer-side scraping/parsing [Task 3]
- Performance guidance that mattered for parity claims: keep runtime sessions long-lived, batch streamed token updates, virtualize long transcript views, and avoid heavy Git/PTY/file parsing in the renderer process [Task 3]

